=========================================================
CONSTRUCTORS AND DESTRUCTORS IN C++ (INTERVIEW NOTES)
=========================================================

CONSTRUCTOR
=========================================================

Definition:
A Constructor is a special member function that is automatically called
when an object is created.

Purpose:
Initialize the object.

Syntax:

class Test
{
public:
    Test()
    {
    }
};

=========================================================
CHARACTERISTICS OF CONSTRUCTORS
=========================================================

1. Same name as class.
2. No return type (not even void).
3. Called automatically.
4. Can be overloaded.
5. Cannot be virtual.
6. Cannot be static.
7. Can have default arguments.

=========================================================
BASIC EXAMPLE
=========================================================

#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class Test
{
public:
    Test()
    {
        cout << "Constructor Called\n";
    }
};

int main()
{
    Test t;
}

Output:
Constructor Called

=========================================================
WHY DO WE NEED CONSTRUCTORS?
=========================================================

Without Constructor:

class Employee
{
public:
    int id;
};

Employee e;

id contains garbage value.

Constructor initializes the object.

=========================================================
TYPES OF CONSTRUCTORS
=========================================================

1. Default Constructor
2. Parameterized Constructor
3. Copy Constructor
4. Move Constructor (C++11)

=========================================================
1. DEFAULT CONSTRUCTOR
=========================================================

Constructor with no parameters.

class Test
{
public:
    Test()
    {
        cout << "Default Constructor";
    }
};

=========================================================
2. PARAMETERIZED CONSTRUCTOR
=========================================================

class Employee
{
public:
    int id;

    Employee(int x)
    {
        id = x;
    }
};

Employee e(100);

=========================================================
3. COPY CONSTRUCTOR
=========================================================

Definition:
Creates a new object as a copy of an existing object.

Syntax:

ClassName(const ClassName& obj);

Example:

class Test
{
public:
    int x;

    Test(int a)
    {
        x = a;
    }

    Test(const Test& obj)
    {
        x = obj.x;
    }
};

Test t1(10);
Test t2 = t1;

=========================================================
WHEN IS COPY CONSTRUCTOR CALLED?
=========================================================

1. Object initialization

Test t2 = t1;

2. Pass by value

fun(Test t);

3. Return by value (before copy elision)

=========================================================
4. MOVE CONSTRUCTOR (C++11)
=========================================================

Definition:
Transfers ownership of resources from a temporary object.

Syntax:

ClassName(ClassName&& obj);

Example:

class Test
{
public:
    Test(Test&& obj)
    {
        cout << "Move Constructor";
    }
};

=========================================================
INITIALIZER LIST
=========================================================

Preferred way of initialization.

class Test
{
    int x;

public:
    Test(int a) : x(a)
    {
    }
};

Advantages:
• Faster
• Mandatory for const members
• Mandatory for reference members

=========================================================
CAN CONSTRUCTORS BE OVERLOADED?
=========================================================

YES.

class Test
{
public:
    Test()
    {
    }

    Test(int x)
    {
    }
};

=========================================================
CONSTRUCTOR CHAINING
=========================================================

Base Constructor
        ↓
Derived Constructor

Example:

class A
{
public:
    A()
    {
        cout << "A\n";
    }
};

class B : public A
{
public:
    B()
    {
        cout << "B\n";
    }
};

Output:

A
B

=========================================================
ORDER OF CONSTRUCTOR CALLS
=========================================================

1. Base Class Constructor
2. Member Object Constructors
3. Derived Constructor Body

=========================================================
EXAMPLE
=========================================================

class Engine
{
};

class Car
{
    Engine e;
};

Construction Order:

Engine
↓
Car

=========================================================
CAN CONSTRUCTOR BE VIRTUAL?
=========================================================

NO.

Reason:
Virtual functions need an object (vptr).

Constructor creates the object.

Object doesn't exist completely yet.

Therefore:

Virtual Constructor is impossible.

=========================================================
CAN CONSTRUCTOR BE STATIC?
=========================================================

NO.

Constructors are associated with object creation.

Static functions belong to the class.

=========================================================
CAN CONSTRUCTOR BE PRIVATE?
=========================================================

YES.

Used in:
Singleton Design Pattern.

=========================================================
DESTRUCTOR
=========================================================

Definition:
A Destructor is a special member function automatically called when an
object is destroyed.

Purpose:
Release resources.

Syntax:

~ClassName()
{
}

=========================================================
CHARACTERISTICS OF DESTRUCTOR
=========================================================

1. Same name as class prefixed with ~
2. No return type
3. Called automatically
4. Only one destructor allowed
5. Cannot be overloaded
6. Can be virtual
7. Cannot be static
8. Cannot have arguments

=========================================================
BASIC EXAMPLE
=========================================================

class Test
{
public:
    ~Test()
    {
        cout << "Destructor";
    }
};

=========================================================
WHY DO WE NEED DESTRUCTORS?
=========================================================

To release:

• Dynamic Memory
• File Handles
• Database Connections
• Sockets
• Mutexes

RAII principle depends on destructors.

=========================================================
EXAMPLE
=========================================================

class Test
{
    int* ptr;

public:
    Test()
    {
        ptr = new int(10);
    }

    ~Test()
    {
        delete ptr;
    }
};

=========================================================
ORDER OF DESTRUCTOR CALLS
=========================================================

Reverse of construction.

Derived Destructor
        ↓
Member Object Destructor
        ↓
Base Destructor

=========================================================
EXAMPLE
=========================================================

class A
{
public:
    ~A()
    {
        cout << "A";
    }
};

class B : public A
{
public:
    ~B()
    {
        cout << "B";
    }
};

Output:

BA

=========================================================
VIRTUAL DESTRUCTOR
=========================================================

Very Important Interview Question.

=========================================================

class Base
{
public:
    virtual ~Base()
    {
        cout << "Base Destructor\n";
    }
};

class Derived : public Base
{
public:
    ~Derived()
    {
        cout << "Derived Destructor\n";
    }
};

Base* ptr = new Derived();

delete ptr;

Output:

Derived Destructor
Base Destructor

=========================================================
WITHOUT VIRTUAL DESTRUCTOR
=========================================================

Base* ptr = new Derived();

delete ptr;

Output:

Base Destructor

Derived Destructor NOT called.

Causes:

Resource Leak.

=========================================================
RULE
=========================================================

If a class has any virtual function,
make its destructor virtual.

=========================================================
CONSTRUCTOR vs DESTRUCTOR
=========================================================

Feature            Constructor          Destructor
---------------------------------------------------------
Purpose            Initialize Object    Cleanup Object
Name               Same as Class        ~ClassName
Arguments          Allowed              Not Allowed
Overloading        Yes                  No
Virtual            No                   Yes
Automatic Call     Object Creation      Object Destruction
Count              Multiple Allowed     Only One

=========================================================
MOST ASKED INTERVIEW QUESTIONS
=========================================================

Q1. Why constructors have no return type?

Answer:
Constructors initialize objects and are called automatically.
Returning a value makes no sense.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q2. Can constructors be virtual?

NO.

Object doesn't exist completely yet.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q3. Can constructors be overloaded?

YES.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q4. Can destructors be overloaded?

NO.

Only one destructor per class.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q5. Can destructors be virtual?

YES.

Required for polymorphic deletion.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q6. Why virtual destructor?

Answer:
Ensures complete destruction of derived objects through base pointers.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q7. What is the order of constructor calls?

Base
↓
Members
↓
Derived

---------------------------------------------------------

Q8. What is the order of destructor calls?

Derived
↓
Members
↓
Base

---------------------------------------------------------

Q9. Can constructor be private?

YES.

Used in Singleton Pattern.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q10. Can destructor be pure virtual?

YES.

But definition is mandatory.

=========================================================
INTERVIEW READY ANSWER (30 Seconds)
=========================================================

Constructors are special member functions used for object initialization
and are automatically called during object creation. They can be
default, parameterized, copy, or move constructors. Destructors are
special member functions used for resource cleanup and are automatically
called during object destruction. In polymorphic base classes,
destructors should always be virtual to ensure proper cleanup.

=========================================================
1-LINE MEMORY TRICK
=========================================================

Constructor
     ↓
Initialization
     ↓
Object Creation

Destructor
     ↓
Cleanup
     ↓
Object Destruction
=========================================================
